#: src/rust-2024/missing-macro-fragment-specifiers.md:1
msgid "Missing macro fragment specifiers"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/missing-macro-fragment-specifiers.md:3
msgid ""
"**NOTE**: This was originally made a hard error only for the 2024 Edition. "
"In Rust 1.89, released after Rust 2024, the lint was made into a hard error "
"in all editions."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/missing-macro-fragment-specifiers.md:5
msgid "Summary"
msgstr "摘要"

#: src/rust-2024/missing-macro-fragment-specifiers.md:7
msgid "The `missing_fragment_specifier` lint is now a hard error."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/missing-macro-fragment-specifiers.md:9
msgid "Details"
msgstr "詳情"

#: src/rust-2024/missing-macro-fragment-specifiers.md:11
msgid ""
"The `missing_fragment_specifier` lint detected a situation when an "
"**unused** pattern in a `macro_rules!` macro definition had a meta-variable "
"(e.g. `$e`) that was not followed by a fragment specifier (e.g. `:expr`). "
"This was made into a hard error in the 2024 Edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/missing-macro-fragment-specifiers.md:16
msgid "// ERROR: missing fragment specifier\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/missing-macro-fragment-specifiers.md:24
msgid ""
"Calling the macro with arguments that would match a rule with a missing "
"specifier (e.g., `foo!($name)`) was a hard error in all editions. However, "
"simply defining a macro with missing fragment specifiers was not, though we "
"did add a lint in Rust 1.17."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/missing-macro-fragment-specifiers.md:26
msgid "Migration"
msgstr "遷移"

#: src/rust-2024/missing-macro-fragment-specifiers.md:28
msgid ""
"To migrate your code to the 2024 Edition, remove the unused matcher rule "
"from the macro."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/missing-macro-fragment-specifiers.md:30
msgid ""
"There is no automatic migration for this change. We expect that this style "
"of macro is extremely rare. The lint was a future-incompatibility lint since "
"Rust 1.17, a deny-by-default lint since Rust 1.20, since Rust 1.82 it warned "
"about dependencies using this pattern, and in Rust 1.89 it became a hard "
"error."
msgstr ""
